---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro'

const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL
const dg = (name: string) => `${base}images/${name}.svg`
---

<BaseLayout>
  <h1>Isobenefit Urbanism — QGIS Plugin</h1>
  <h6>Brainstorming walkable urban growth on real-world data</h6>

  <section>
    <p>
      The <strong>Isobenefit Urbanism</strong> plugin for QGIS simulates how a place could grow so that
      everyone keeps walkable access to <strong>both</strong> local centres (shops, services) <strong>and</strong>
      green space. From the simulation it generates a <strong>recommended plan</strong> for further discussion
      with planning experts. It runs on your own GIS layers, and it explores options rather than prescribing
      them.
    </p>
    <figure id="hero-plan">
      <img class="hero" src={dg('demo_recommended_plan')} alt="A recommended plan for Cambourne: new settlements with walkable centres woven through a green matrix around the existing town" />
      <figcaption>A recommended plan for <strong>Cambourne</strong>, grown from the downloaded layers shown
      below. New settlements (dark grey) with their centres (red) join the existing town (brown), and every
      home stays within a walk of a centre and of green. The same example is used throughout this
      page.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <nav class="toc">
      <a href="#concept">Concept</a>
      <a href="#install">Install</a>
      <a href="#inputs">Data</a>
      <a href="#grid">From layers to cells</a>
      <a href="#simulation">The simulation</a>
      <a href="#plan">From runs to a plan</a>
      <a href="#postprocessing">Post-processing</a>
      <a href="#outputs">Outputs</a>
      <a href="#scenarios">Scenarios</a>
      <a href="#parameters">Parameters</a>
      <a href="#departures">Departures</a>
      <a href="#credits">Credits</a>
    </nav>
  </section>

  <h2 id="concept">Concept &amp; rationale</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      <a href="https://lucadacci.wixsite.com/dacci/isobenefit-urbanism-morphogenesis">Isobenefit Urbanism</a>
      (Luca D'Acci) describes a city whose benefits are spread <em>evenly</em> — <em>iso</em> as in
      <em>equal</em>: wherever you live, and however large the settlement grows, you can walk both to a local
      centre and to green land. Quality of life shouldn't depend on which corner of town you live in. The
      aim is to avoid both <strong>sprawl</strong> (people stranded far from centres, nature paved over) and
      <strong>overcrowding</strong> (nature squeezed out).
    </p>
    <p>
      It also sits between master-planning and laissez-faire growth: a few simple rules <em>guide</em>
      development, while the detailed form is left to emerge. The plugin works the same way: a
      <strong>cellular-automaton</strong> simulation grows a grid of land cells step by step under rules that
      keep new development on foot of a centre and protect green corridors. The rules include randomness, so
      no single run is "the" answer — the plugin runs many, and reports the <strong>variation</strong> across
      runs as well as a single <strong>recommended plan</strong>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="install">Install the plugin</h2>
  <section>
    <ol>
      <li>
        In QGIS (3.x or 4.x): <em>Plugins → Manage and Install Plugins → Settings →</em> tick
        <em>"Show also experimental plugins"</em>, then search for <strong>isobenefit</strong> and install it.
      </li>
      <li>
        On first run it checks for the <code>isobenefit</code> simulation engine and, if missing, offers to
        install it into the QGIS Python environment (needs internet). <strong>Restart QGIS</strong> afterwards.
      </li>
    </ol>
    <p>
      If automatic install is blocked, run it yourself with the QGIS Python:
    </p>
    <pre><code>&lt;qgis-python&gt; -m pip install "isobenefit&gt;=0.10,&lt;0.11"</code></pre>
    <p>
      <strong>Why two pieces?</strong> The plugin itself is thin (UI + GIS I/O). The heavy compute is a
      separate Rust engine published to PyPI as the <code>isobenefit</code> package — kept apart because the
      QGIS plugin repository doesn't permit shipping compiled binaries. Source for both:
      <a href="https://github.com/UCL/BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin">BSP-isobenefit-qgis-plugin</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="inputs">Step 1 — Download the data</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      A companion <strong>Extract from OpenStreetMap</strong> tool downloads all of the input layers for an
      area of interest, so no manual data preparation is needed. The
      panels below are <strong>the downloaded layers</strong> for a 4.2 km window around Cambourne, fetched
      with the plugin's own queries. Each shows one layer of the same place: green doesn't overlap built,
      centres sit inside the built fabric, and stacked together they re-make the town.
    </p>
    <div class="layer-grid">
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_extents')} alt="" /><figcaption>Extents — the area of interest (the only <em>required</em> layer)</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_built')} alt="" /><figcaption>Existing built fabric — frozen; never redeveloped</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_green')} alt="" /><figcaption>Green space — preserved by the growth rules</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_centres')} alt="" /><figcaption>Urban centres — retail/commercial areas; every covered cell is a centre</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_unbuildable')} alt="" /><figcaption>Unbuildable — water, industrial, and buffered barrier corridors (the A428)</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_industrial')} alt="" /><figcaption>Industrial land — kept, but no new housing on it</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_streets')} alt="" /><figcaption>Street network — classed; groundwork for walk routing</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="layer" src={dg('input_pt')} alt="" /><figcaption>Public-transport stops — groundwork for transit-aware growth</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>
      Two further datasets — <em>railways</em> and <em>rail/tram stations</em> — are downloaded too, but are
      <strong>empty here</strong>: Cambourne has no railway. Where stations exist, they anchor centres in the
      recommended plan.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img class="hero" src={dg('input_composite')} alt="All downloaded layers stacked into one map of Cambourne" />
      <figcaption><strong>All layers together.</strong> Throughout this page, vector shapes are
      <em>data</em> and dots are <em>simulation</em>.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <h2 id="grid">Step 2 — From layers to cells</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      In QGIS you point the run dialog at these layers, choose a projected CRS and an output path, and press
      Run; the rest is automatic. The simulation works on a grid (here 50 m cells), so the vector layers are
      rasterised first: existing built fabric becomes <em>frozen</em> built cells, downloaded green becomes
      protected green cells, centre <em>areas</em> become centre cells across their full extent, and water,
      industrial land and buffered motorway-class corridors are marked <strong>unbuildable</strong>, so the
      simulation never develops them. Every run on this page starts from this grid:
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img class="hero" src={dg('demo_substrate')} alt="Cambourne rasterised to the simulation grid" />
      <figcaption><strong>The town as cells.</strong> Brown = existing built (frozen), magenta = existing
      centres, blue = unbuildable cells (note the A428 corridor and the waterways), small green = free land.
      The real street network stays visible beneath the dots.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <h2 id="simulation">Step 3 — The simulation</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Each step, the cellular automaton visits the land grid and decides whether an undeveloped cell may be
      built. The rules, zoomed into a schematic neighbourhood:
    </p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_0')} alt="Step 0: population target" /><figcaption>Stop once the target population is reached; otherwise keep growing.</figcaption></figure>
    <p>Step 1 — a cell is a candidate only if it is empty <em>and</em> on the periphery of built land:</p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_1a')} alt="" /><figcaption>An already-built cell — nothing to do, skip.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_1b')} alt="" /><figcaption>An empty cell not touching built land — not on the periphery, skip.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_1c')} alt="" /><figcaption>An empty cell touching built land — on the periphery, so a candidate → continue.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_2')} alt="Step 2: centre walk" /><figcaption>The candidate must be within a <em>centre walk</em> of a centrality — so new homes stay near a centre.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_3')} alt="Step 3: green span" /><figcaption>Building must not shrink a green corridor below the <em>minimum green span</em> — protecting access to nature.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('step_4')} alt="Step 4: build" /><figcaption>If every check passes the cell is built; its density is set by walking distance to the nearest centre — denser closer in, within the configured range.</figcaption></figure>
    <p>
      Two distinct green thresholds are at play. The <em>green span</em> above is a <strong>build rule</strong> —
      a minimum corridor width the simulation won't crimp. The separate <em>green walk</em> — how far a home may
      be from usable green — is a <strong>walkable-access target</strong> scored on the finished plan, alongside
      the centre walk.
    </p>
    <h3>Where new centres come from</h3>
    <p>
      As built land outgrows a walk of any centre, the simulation seeds a new <em>neighbouring</em> centre — so a
      single town can keep growing outward. The <strong>Dispersed development</strong> dial (Off / Moderate /
      Aggressive) is a separate control: it sets only how readily development <em>leapfrogs</em> away from the
      core to start satellite settlements.
    </p>
    <div class="diagram-pair">
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('centres_neighbouring')} alt="" /><figcaption>A <em>neighbouring</em> centre seeds where built land outgrows a walk of any centre.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('centres_isolated')} alt="" /><figcaption>An <em>isolated</em> centre lets a satellite settlement leapfrog away from the core.</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <h3>The rules at work on the real town</h3>
    <p>
      Here are those rules running on the Cambourne grid from Step 2 — the same run at three points in
      time. New
      development (dark) stays on the periphery of the existing fabric, keeps within a walk of a centre (red
      seeds appear as the town outgrows them), and leaves the green corridors and unbuildable cells alone:
    </p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_growth_006')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Iteration 6</strong> — first infill at the edges of the existing fabric</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_growth_030')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Iteration 30</strong> — settlements consolidate; new centres have seeded</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_growth_final')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Target met</strong> — the raw grown state, before any post-processing</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>
      Two further dials shape growth: <strong>build probability</strong> (the per-step growth rate — lower is
      tighter and more compact, higher is faster and looser) and the <strong>density range</strong> (min–max),
      which the engine spreads as a gradient toward centres: the closer a block is to a centre, the denser
      it is. The mean stays at the midpoint of the range, so the population total is unaffected.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="plan">Step 4 — From many runs to one plan</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      A single run is one plausible outcome; a different random seed gives a different, equally valid
      layout. So the plugin runs an <strong>ensemble</strong> and does two things with it.
    </p>
    <div class="diagram-pair">
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_ensemble')} alt="" /><figcaption>Average the runs into <em>likelihood</em> layers: an uncertainty map of where development is robust vs contingent.</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_select')} alt="" /><figcaption>A probability surface isn't a buildable plan — so also pick the single best run (shortest average walk to amenities).</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>Here is the real likelihood layer for Cambourne — twenty-four runs blended:</p>
    <figure>
      <img class="hero" src={dg('demo_likelihood')} alt="Development likelihood over Cambourne from 24 blended runs" />
      <figcaption><strong>Development likelihood.</strong> Dark cells end up built in most runs (robust);
      faint cells only in a few (contingent). It shows where growth tends to go, but it is not itself
      a plan — which is why a best single run is also selected.</figcaption>
    </figure>
  </section>

  <h2 id="postprocessing">Step 5 — Post-processing the chosen run</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      The chosen run is tidied into the recommended plan. Post-processing deliberately changes <strong>only the
      centres</strong> (plus a gentle building cleanup) — the buildings come from the simulation.
    </p>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_cleanup')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Cleanup:</strong> tiny stranded settlements below the minimum size revert to green. It's gentle, and the raw plan is saved too, so the change stays visible.</figcaption></figure>
    <figure><img class="diagram" src={dg('plan_centring')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Centre placement:</strong> each centre is moved to the <em>interior</em> of its contiguous built area — on built land and central to it, never on an edge or in a gap.</figcaption></figure>
    <p>
      Finally, centres are offered at two <strong>clustering</strong> strengths — the same run, the same
      buildings, only the centre arrangement differs. These are the two options the plugin actually writes:
    </p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_clustering_moderate')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Moderately clustered</strong> — more, smaller centres; shorter walks</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_clustering_tight')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Tightly clustered</strong> — fewer, larger centres; more consolidated</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
    <p>
      Compare either against the raw grown state at the end of <a href="#simulation">Step 3</a> — the raw plan
      is always saved alongside, so everything post-processing did stays visible.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="outputs">Step 6 — Outputs</h2>
  <section>
    <p>An ensemble run writes a small set of layers, each shown above:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>existing development</strong> — the baseline (the starting grid in <a href="#grid">Step 2</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>raw (before post-processing)</strong> — the chosen run as grown (end of <a href="#simulation">Step 3</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>moderately / tightly clustered centres</strong> — the two recommended-plan options (<a href="#postprocessing">Step 5</a>)</li>
      <li><strong>development likelihood</strong> (built, green) — the ensemble uncertainty map (<a href="#plan">Step 4</a>)</li>
      <li><strong><code>_report.txt</code></strong> — a record of the parameters and per-option statistics</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      (A <em>single</em> run — the ensemble checkbox off — is instead written iteration by iteration as a
      temporal growth animation you can play in the QGIS Temporal Controller; the three growth moments in
      <a href="#simulation">Step 3</a> are exactly such frames.)
    </p>
    <p>
      The figure <a href="#hero-plan">at the top of the page</a> is the moderately-clustered recommended plan
      from exactly this pipeline.
    </p>
  </section>

  <h2 id="scenarios">Scenarios — the dials on the same town</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      Every figure below is a <strong>real pipeline run on the same Cambourne grid</strong>; only the named
      dial changes between figures.
    </p>

    <h3>Dispersed development</h3>
    <p>
      How readily growth leapfrogs away from the existing fabric. Even <em>Moderate</em> keeps the existing
      town dominant; <em>Aggressive</em> scatters satellites across the window.
    </p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_off')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Off</strong> — growth only at the existing fabric's edges</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_moderate')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Moderate</strong> — the town leads; a few satellites</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_dispersal_aggressive')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Aggressive</strong> — many scattered satellites</figcaption></figure>
    </div>

    <h3>Build probability</h3>
    <p>The per-step growth rate: over the same number of steps, faster growth reaches much further.</p>
    <div class="demo-row">
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_buildprob_slow')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Slow (0.08)</strong> — tight, compact growth</figcaption></figure>
      <figure><img class="demo" src={dg('demo_buildprob_fast')} alt="" /><figcaption><strong>Fast (0.6)</strong> — far more grown in the same time</figcaption></figure>
    </div>
  </section>

  <h2 id="parameters">Parameters</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      The run dialog groups the controls into <strong>Simulation</strong>, <strong>Walkable access</strong>,
      <strong>Post-processing</strong>, <strong>Density</strong> and <strong>Output &amp; input layers</strong>.
      The key controls, with their defaults:
    </p>
    <div class="flex justify-center overflow-x-auto">
      <table>
        <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Default</th><th>What it does</th></tr>
        <tr><td>Grid size</td><td>50 m</td><td>Cell size of the simulation grid</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Max iterations</td><td>100</td><td>Cap on growth steps</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Target population</td><td>100,000</td><td>Growth stops once reached</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Build probability</td><td>0.25</td><td>Per-step growth rate (tighter ↔ faster)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Dispersed development</td><td>Moderate</td><td>Leapfrog rate — Off / Moderate / Aggressive</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Centre walk</td><td>400 m</td><td>How near a home must be to a centre</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Green walk</td><td>400 m</td><td>How near a home must be to green (scored on the plan)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Min settlement area</td><td>2 ha</td><td>Smaller stranded new clusters revert to green</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Min green span</td><td>400 m</td><td>Minimum green-corridor width (a build rule)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Density (min–max)</td><td>1500–6000 /km²</td><td>Gradient toward centres (denser closer in)</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Existing-built density</td><td>2000 /km²</td><td>Assumed density of existing fabric</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Detail (ensemble)</td><td>Standard — 50 runs</td><td>How many runs to blend / choose from</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <h2 id="departures">Departures from standard Isobenefit Urbanism</h2>
  <section>
    <p>
      The growth rules themselves — periphery-only development, a walk to the nearest centrality, protected
      green spans, stochastic seeding of new centralities — follow D'Acci's morphogenesis and Voto's original
      simulator. Around that core, this tool adds several things of its own, listed here so it is clear what comes
      from the theory and what we added:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Ensembles instead of a single run.</strong> The original simulator produces a single run.
        We run many, blend them into likelihood layers, and select the best single run by shortest average
        walk to amenities.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Post-processing of the chosen run.</strong> The original keeps centres exactly where they
        seeded. We add a gentle cleanup (stranded specks below a minimum settlement size revert to green) and
        re-position centres to the interior of the development they serve, offered at two clustering
        strengths. The raw grown state is always saved alongside, so the edit is transparent.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Density as a gradient toward centres.</strong> The original draws each block's density
        randomly from fixed tiers. We set density by walking distance to the nearest centre (denser closer
        in), holding the mean so population accounting is unchanged.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Separate centre-walk and green-walk thresholds.</strong> The original uses one walkable
        radius; we let each amenity have its own, and score the finished plan against both.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Real-data grounding.</strong> Existing fabric is frozen (never redeveloped); water,
        industrial land and motorway-class corridors are carved out as unbuildable; downloaded centre
        <em>areas</em> act as true multi-cell centres; and an OSM extraction tool supplies all of it. Streets
        and public-transport stops are downloaded as groundwork — the growth rules do not use them yet.
      </li>
    </ul>
  </section>

